<h4 id="group-definition">Group Definition</h4>
<p>group: set of elements</p>
<ol>
  <li>Operation: *   such as, addition, multiplication</li>
  <li>Closed under Operation: *</li>
  <li>Inverses: inverses exists for all x</li>
  <li>Identity element: e</li>
  <li>associative: \((A\ast B)\ast C\)=\(A\ast (B\ast C)\)</li>
</ol>

<h5 id="remark">Remark</h5>
<p>why we need these properties ? <br />
The answer is we want to solve equation. <br />
<img src="/images/abstract-algebra-group-reason.png" /></p>

<p>we say elements, not numbers, because elements are more abstract.
Identity element: an element that leaves any element of the set to which it belongs unchanged when combined with it by a specified operation.
such as 0 in the set of all integers under addition or 1 in the set of positive integers under multiplication.
<br /></p>

<p><img src="/images/abstract-algebra-group.png" />
<br /></p>

<h4 id="remark-1">remark</h4>
<p>According to group definition, group may not be commutative, which means: <br />
\(x\ast y \neq y \ast x\)</p>

<h4 id="abelian-group">Abelian Group</h4>
<p>Given G is a group, if G is commutative, then G is called <strong>commutative group</strong>
or <strong>Abelian Group</strong>  <br /> If G is not commutative, then G is called
<strong>noncommutative group</strong>.</p>
<ol>
  <li>Convention, most of the time, when we talk about commutative groups,we will
write the star as addition(+), that’s convenient for commutative groups.</li>
</ol>

<h4 id="subgroup">Subgroup</h4>
<p>H is used to denote subgroup, why, because H after G in alphabet ahahaha…
Don’t say mathematician are predictable <br /></p>
<ol>
  <li>\(H \leq G\) can be read H is a subgroup of G.</li>
  <li>\(H &lt; G\)  H is a proper subgroup of G.</li>
</ol>

<h4 id="terminology-4--order">terminology 4:  Order</h4>
<p>The order of groups is the number of elements in the group.</p>

<h4 id="terminolgy-5-cayley-tables">terminolgy 5: Cayley Tables</h4>
<p>Properties:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Every row/column contains identity element</li>
  <li>Symmetric about diagonal, if the group is abelian.</li>
  <li>No duplicate elements in row and columns
<br /></li>
</ol>

<p><img src="/images/abstract-algebra-cayley-table.png" />
<br /></p>
