<p><img src="/images/abstract-algebra-caey-table-order3.png" /></p>

<h4 id="subgroup-1">Subgroup</h4>
<p>Gaussian used to partition the number integer into a few sets by mod, and treat new sets as a new number. <br />
In group theory, this can be done by <strong>normal group</strong> ,and the result is <strong>quotient group</strong>. <br /></p>
<ol>
  <li>In general, we can define the following:
\(Z_n for n=1,2,3,\cdots
Z_n = {0,1,\cdots,n-1}\)
The operation is + = addition(mod n) <br />
Here, the symbol + means group operation for expecially for commutative group.
Actually group operation is addition plus mod n</li>
</ol>

<p>For example, Z mod 5, the following is the amazing part: we get five new numbers <strong>0,1,2,3,4</strong>. <br /></p>
<ol>
  <li>r=0: \({\cdots,-15,-10,-5,0,5,10,15,\cdots}\)</li>
  <li>r=1: \({\cdots,-14,-9,-4,1,6,11,16,\cdots}\)</li>
  <li>r=2: \({\cdots,-13,-8,-3,2,7,12,17,\cdots}\)</li>
  <li>r=3: \({\cdots,-12,-7,-2,3,8,13,18,\cdots}\)</li>
  <li>r=4: \({\cdots,-11,-6,-1,4,9,14,19,\cdots}\)
The amazing thing is the five numbers form a new group under addition. <br /></li>
  <li>The identity number is r=0: <br /></li>
  <li>each set has an inverse: r=1 and r=4, r=2 and r=3</li>
</ol>

<p>Using the group theory:
<br />
<img src="/images/abstract-algebra-subgroup.png" />
<br /></p>

<p>In here, the group operation <br />
$a \times b = (a+b)mod(5)$</p>

<h4 id="concept">concept</h4>

<p>Groups, rings, and fields are familiar objects to us, we just haven’t used those terms. Roughly, these are all sets of elements with additional structure
(that is, various way of combining elements to produce an elements of the set)</p>
<ol>
  <li>group: a set in which you can perform one operation, usually addition or multiplicaation mod n for us with some nice properties.</li>
  <li>ring:  a ring is a set equipped with two operations, called addition and multiplication.</li>
  <li>field: a field is a group under both addition and multiplication.</li>
</ol>

<h4 id="term">term</h4>
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Algebraic dual space: Given any space \(V\) over a field \(F\), the <strong>algebraic dual space</strong> \(V^{*}\) is defined as the set of all linear
maps 
\(\phi: V \rightarrow F\)</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>elements in the dual space are linear functional.</p>
  </li>
</ol>

